# Agent Deck

<!-- agent-deck:harness:start -->
**Connect first:** Ensure Agent Deck MCP is connected before using deck tools (`agent-deck setup --client cursor|claude --start`, then restart the host). Claude Code: `claude mcp list` should show agent-deck as Connected when the backend is running.

**Session opener (first turn only):** When Agent Deck MCP is connected and this is a new conversation in a workspace, call `get_decks`, then `bind_workspace` with the project root and a `deckId` (if `.agent-deck/use.json` exists, use its `deckId`), then `get_session_binding`, and tell the user **exactly one line** using `display_summary` (e.g. `ā—† dev Ā· 2 MCP Ā· 0 keys Ā· 1 playbooks`). This is the deck-status line for IDE Agent chat ā€” there is no host footer there. Do **not** repeat it every turn unless the user asks or the bind changes (`switch_bound_deck`, new repo).

**Later turns:** Call `bind_workspace` before the first deck-scoped tool if not already bound. Terminal hosts may also show the deck in the prompt footer via `statusLine`; do not duplicate unless the user asks.

Before declining for missing tools (Slack, Linear, GitHub, etc.), use agent-deck MCP: `bind_workspace`, `get_bound_deck`, `call_service_tool`. Don't hardcode deck IDs.

Deck playbooks are task recipes ā€” thin trigger stubs from `agent-deck use` plus `get_bound_deck` / `get_playbook`. **Never** mirror playbook bodies into `.cursor/skills/`, rules, or Claude skills ā€” one source of truth on the deck; stubs are pointers only.

### Playbooks ā€” refine from outcomes (self-improvement)

**When the user corrects your output** (the write trigger ā€” no need to have called `get_playbook` earlier in the session):

**Update case** (a playbook covered this task): fix the output, then `propose_playbook_patch` with item ops ā€” prefer one `add_item` to Gotchas/Checklist; include `evidence.user_feedback_excerpt` as a short verbatim quote of the correction.

**Genesis case** (no playbook covered the task): before ending, `propose_playbook_patch { kind: "create", new_playbook: { title, triggers, body with one gotcha } }` ā€” a few lines is the right size.

**Explicit user-directed playbook edits** ("fix the playbook to say X"): `update_playbook` ā€” they already reviewed.

Tell the user in one line that a proposal was filed; review happens in the dashboard.

**How to shape proposals:** generalize project-specific names but keep concrete gotchas; place lessons in Checklist/Gotchas; use `rewrite_body` only when structure cannot absorb the lesson.

In this repo: run `agent-deck use <deck>` once (writes MCP + trigger stubs + `.agent-deck/use.json`). `bind_workspace` with the workspace root and that `deckId`. When a task matches a stub or deck `triggers`, `get_playbook` before improvising. After accepting playbook patches that change triggers, run `agent-deck use --refresh`.
<!-- agent-deck:harness:end -->
